<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=101243464036903></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f101243464036903><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=journal.html?user=49677&mid=101243464036903>Oh, the pain...</a> <a id=fs8 href=journal.html?user=49677&mid=101243464036903#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=49677><span id=Guru>alaaraaf the Puissant</span></a>, <span id=Guru>Guru</span><br><span id=notbold>166 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Wed, Jan 30th 7:52 PM 2002</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent<span id=notbold>[5.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Hey.<br><br>Successfully gained level forty-eight today.&nbsp;&nbsp;Still well on target for getting my spells.  (Currently one yellow into the level.)  Giving in a little early tonight, since I can't find anything useful, or amusing to fight.<br><br>My inclination toward finding interesting things to play with, led to a rather unpleasant encounter.  I have, as I have mentioned before, a small and fairly twinked shaman.  Most of his gear s Scaled Mystic, which I have quested.  I went for a wander in the Swamp of No Hope, looking for Froglok treated planks, to add another item to his wardrobe.  I got bored of slaughtering the inhabitents of the Froglok village pretty quickly and thought I'd go take a look at the Froglok temple close to the zone line on the East side of the swamp.  (Trakannon's teeth, perhaps?)<br><br>As I wandered through the swamp, certain that nothing that dared to attack would be much of a challenge, I noticed my pet had vanished.  Annoying, but this happens.  When I looked at my chat window, I discovered he had fought something and, apparently, lost.  Even more shocking, he had taunted but once, from attack to death.  <i>What could possibly kill my pet that swiftly in a newbie zone???</i>  Because I am brave, courageous, undaunted in the face of unthinkable odds and generally unaware of my own limitations, I summoned another pet and went looking for the assailant.  <i>(Now you just know that's gotta be a mistake, don't ya?)</i><br><br>I found, or perhaps more accurately stumbled across the villain.  A Froglok named <a href=HTTP://eqbeastiary.allakhazam.com/search.shtml?id=5318 target=_new>Ulump Pujluk</a>.  Before I could assess whether I should fight, or flee, I was lying on the ground, pretending to be dead, with a little under half health.  <i>(Smothered in bone dust, from the shattered remnants of a second pet, no less.)</i>  In the few seconds it took to notice him, he had killed my pet and hit me three times!  Twice for 225 points of damage!  Unsuprisingly, when I appraised my foe, he considered red.  Even worse, the accursed Froglok betrayed no intention of moving away from my prone body.<br><br>At this point, things got even worse!  <i>(How is this even feasible, when lying at the feet of a giant killer Froglok, I hear you cry!?!)</i>  I held the shift key a few seconds and heard a beep.  I knew at this point, things did not look too good.  (I am using Windows XP.  If you hold the shift key, you get a nice lil pop-up, asking if you want to switch on a feature called 'sticky-keys'.)  This of course caused EverQuest to crash.<br><br>I took the opportunity to look Ulump up at this point.  No good news there.  He's level fifty-five and part of the druid epic.  Which of course means he's probably more like level sixty, than fifty-five!  I left things be, for a bit in the hope he'd get bored and go away.  <br><br>I log back in.  Looks good.  At least at the character selection screen, I'm still in the swamp and, more importantly, not naked.  But, when I reappear, he's still there.  *Sigh*  I immediately hit my hotkey for Feign Death and drop to the floor.  <br><br>There's no-one in my guild, who's in a position to try to drag an epic mob off me, so I decide to bite the bullet.  I jump up and run.  And, suprisingly, I am left unmolested.  When considered, he scowls at me, but doesn't actually opt to open me up.  <i>(I'm not gonna complein about this!)</i><br><br>I <b>still</b> have no idea why he took such affront to my pet.  Maybe when I next see a druid who's pursuing his epic weapon, I'll tag along and ask the accursed Froglok, as he exhales his final breaths...<br><br>On the other hand...<br><br>As level fifty-one approaches, I'm rather looking forward to the chance to play with the new Alternative Advancement skills.  However, I was today advised that each point of AA experience costs about the same as completing level fifty!  Ugh!  I guess I won't be using these for a while after all.  Damn.<br><br>One of the necromancer Class enhancements, is the ability to use a buff as a mass group buff.  The short description is something like this:<br><LI>Refresh time of seventy-two minutes.<br><LI>Use a beneficial buff as an area effect buff.<br><LI>Doubles mana cost of casting.<br><br>I've been wondering for a few days, what the developer at Verant thought he was doing, when he put this in as a necromancer enhancement.  I mean, we're not exactly a buffing class, are we now???  However, I think I have actually found a use for this diabolical piece of laziness...<br><br><b>The <u>perfect</u> mana battery:</b><br>Necromancers get a couple of spells that allows them to 'donate' mana to another person.  The best of these, gives 100 mana, for a casting cost of 300 mana.  <i>(Covetous subversion.)  </i>It's not particularly impressive, but it seems the main role of many high level necromancers is to pump mana into clerics.  *Sigh*  Doesn't sound like much fun, does it.<br>But, with the new 'mass group buff' enhancement, necromancers may have finally evolved into a mana battery that will make them more than desirable.<br>Using the spell and the enhancement, a single necromancer could cast an area effect mana dump of 100 mana, costing him 600 mana.  But, this isn't actually the best part.<br>Imagine a huddle of six necromancers.  Each casts Covetous Subversion as a group buff.  Each necromancer expends <b>and</b> receives 600 mana.  Not very exciting...  You cast a spell, it has no effect and costs you nothing.  *Shrug*<br>But, because this is an area effect spell, anyone else who cuddles in to the necromancers gets a jolt of mana.  Since the models are hollow, I would imagine you could fit a good many people into this huddle.<br>Now isn't that cool?<br><br>The sad thing, is that even if this works, it's screaming out for nerfing.  *Sigh*  It's not <b>really</b> overpowered, since there is a seventy-two minute timer on the area effect buff ability.  But you just know that if it works out, it'll be nerfed, the second someone figures it out and uses it.  Bah!<br><br>Just remember, you saw it here first!  *Grin*<br><br><span style='color: purple;'><LI>Disclaimer:<br>I don't know if this will work.  I don't see any reason why it shouldn't, but that's not the same as having tried it out.  As I said above, I can't even play with the general AA abilities yet.<br>Having said which, I mentioned my idea to a level sixty necromancer, who got rather excited at the suggestion.  So, either both of us were insane, or my idea isn't too far fetched.<br>I'd be very happy if it did work.  It's really the only use for a rather stupid and misplaced ability.  <i>(It costs nine points...  That's a whole lot of experience!!!)</i></span style='color: purple;'><br><br>One more happy thought...<br><br>I went to the Bazaar a few days ago.  (To buy my level forty-nine spells, no less!)  The Bazaar is still a grotesque dissapointment.  (Another thing allowed to slide, in an attempt to take the customer's money, before the product was finished.  (Wait, wait!  I have to keep my bitterness in check.  After all, this is a happy thought...))<br>I noticed that Merchant Tekrama (sp?) no longer had an apostrophe before his name.  And, he's now open for business.  Among the items he had for sale was '<a href=HTTP://everquest.allakhazam.com/db/item.html?item=8748 target=_new>a Trader's satchel</a>'.  Follow the link, to see what it is.  In short, it's:<br><LI>Ten slots.<br><LI>Giant size.<br><LI>No weght reduction.<br><LI>Twenty-five weight.<br><LI>Container.<br>Twenty-five weight???  I can see every monk in Norrath scrambling to buy one of those!  I looked at it, decided it was more insane junk and maybe for a quest and wandered off.  Having asked my guild if they had any ideas.  Of course, they were just as bemused as I was!<br><br>However, having read the thread on the page detailing the satchel, it's been suggested this is the container you will use to set yourself up as a merchant, in the Bazaar!  I guess this suggestion could turn out to be false.  But, it makes a lot of sense and gives me some hope.<br><br>A working Bazaar would be a wonderful thing...<br><br>Anyhow, that's it for tonight.  Time for me to sleep and dream.  It doesn't matter what about, since I never remember anyhow.  *Shrug*  Well, except the nightmares.  They stay with me.  They just don't go away.<br><br>...Cold toes again...<br>...Gonna have circulatory problems when I'm old...<br>...*Sigh*...<br><br>G'night.<br><br>AlAaraaf.<br><br>&nbsp;<br>"Te aurdire no possum. Musa sapienum fixa est in aura."</td></tr>
