	   <tr><td colspan=2>Hey.<br><br>Once again, I have been caught unaware by patching.&nbsp;&nbsp;This time, it's not my fault.  For some reason of their own, the nice people at Sony have decided to work on the servers without telling anyone in advance.  *Shrug*  <br><br>I finally broke free of level forty-five yesterday.  I have half a blue bubble of experience, so I need to be careful for a bit.  <i>(Given the horrific experience loss in levels following Hell levels, I need to be <b>really</b> careful.)</i><br><br><span style='color: red;'><i>As a small aside, aren't Hell levels and the penalties in the following levels a <b>really</b> cynical way of making people play longer?  I mean, they could have used something like alternate advancement, to prolong my playing time...  Or added extra levels...  Or added <b>good</b> quests.  (I mean interesting quests, or quests where the experience reward is realistic.  As opposed to what we have, which is a quest which is done purely for the reward item.)  Nope, these things are all too much like hard work.  Lets just make five levels that are twice as long and another five with a double experience loss penalty.  (And this is of course just in the run up to level fifty.  I don't even know how bad it gets after that!!!)<br>I read somewhere once, that it was a programming bug and Verant were just too lazy to fix it.  I don't believe that for a second.  I'm with the cynical point of view on this one.</i></span style='color: red;'><br><br><i>.....&quot;I put my trust in you,&quot;<br>.....&quot;Pushed as far as I can go,&quot;<br>.....&quot;And for all this,&quot;<br>.....&quot;Theres only one thing you should know,&quot;<br>.....&quot;I tried so hard,&quot;<br>.....&quot;And got so far,&quot;<br>.....&quot;But in the end,&quot;<br>.....&quot;It doesnt even matter,&quot;<br>.....&quot;I had to fall,&quot;<br>.....&quot;And lose it all,&quot;<br>.....&quot;But in the end,&quot;<br>.....&quot;It doesnt even matter,&quot;</i><br><br>Anyhow, I have an exam tomorrow and then I have eight days in which to drag myself up a couple more levels.  New (and ever more diabolical) spells at level forty-nine.  I'm looking forward to that.  Even better, I start getting spells at every level, after level fifty.<br><br>I have wondered, from time to time, why Verant didn't do something more like that at the lower levels.  Say you get two spells per level, instead of ten every five levels.  I'm sure it'd be far more motivating.  (And a motivated player is playing and paying their subscription, instead of getting bored and quitting.)  I guess either I'm missing something, I'm a marketing genius and can see things no-one at Sony can, or they're all morons.  Take your pick.  (You know I <b>have</b> to go with the, 'I'm a genius' line here!  *Grin*<br><br>Another similar line of thought I have wondered, is why Sony insist that you must buy a copy of the game, to create a new account.  The reason this came up, is that I have a friend, who would play EverQuest.  (We used to play an old text MUD together and he practically drools when he sees EverQuest!  (I mean this in the most vile and literal way!  *Giggle*))  But, he won't buy the game.  If, I had been able to loan him my disks and Sony would let him have an account for free, he'd have been playing for months and they'd have had his money.  But instead, they have nothing.  Because they choose to be grasping about the profits.  <i>(I bought the issue of PCZone that has the free copy of the original EverQuest a few days ago, so I'll givve him that.)</i>  Obviously, my genius allows me to see things that no-one at Sony are capable of realising.  *Shrug*<br><br>The tags showing which journals have new posts work <b><span style='color: orange;'>spectacularly</span style='color: orange;'></b> well.  I've had a couple of hundred hits, since the last post!  Normally the hits trickle along, as people check in to see if there's anything new, every so often.  Of course, it does make me wonder if anyone's going to see this post.  (After all, the tag stays for thirty-six hours after a new post and I'm not exactly in the habit of posting particularly frequently.)  <br><br>And that about wraps up all I have to say for the day.  It's time I go out and do some shopping and then I have laundry to to!  <i>(Oh yes indeedy, the excitement of my real life explains why I play EverQuest only too well, doesn't it?)</i><br><br><i>.....&quot;I should be many things.&quot;<br>.....&quot;One day, I may be!&quot;</i><br><br><span style='color: purple;'><b>Sidenotes:</b><br><LI>The first (long'ish) quote is from a song by Linkin' Park, called, 'In the end'.  I'm not really a Linkin' Park fan, but I downloaded a video of this song, with clips of FMV from Final Fantasy VII.  And I'm enjoying it greatly.  (And, more to the point, I found the lyrics to be enchanting and thought I'd share them with you.)<br><LI>The second quote is one of mine.  Just so you're not wondering where I stole it.<br><LI>I found the stuffed barracuda!  (If you haven't read the post about goblin hunting, this will make no sense to you.  So go and read it!)  He's a static spawn between the two northern spires of the Temple of Veksar.  As I said before he cons <span style='color: green;'>green</span style='color: green;'> at level forty-five.  I'd guess he's under level twenty, having killed him, on mercenary contract for someone.  He drops a skull that's apparently used in one of the Iksar shaman cudgel quests.<br><LI>My feet are cold!  Well, actually, it's just my toes.</span style='color: purple;'><br><br>And that's it...<br><br>AlAaraaf.<br><br>&nbsp;<br>"Te aurdire no possum. Musa sapienum fixa est in aura."</td></tr>
