	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Tue, Jan 22nd 11:19 AM 2002</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent<span id=notbold>[5.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Hey.<br><br>Do ya realise that I started this journal on November seventh and my post included a remark about having attained level forty-one?&nbsp;&nbsp;<i>Nope, 'cos it's completely irrelevant!  Hah!</i>  I'm now level forty-five.  So, apparently in something like ten weeks, I have climbed the grand total of four levels.  (Which given that I broke through levels forty-two and forty-three in two days, is even more disturbing!)<br><br>I'm beginning to think that the only people levelling slower than me have accounts that they've cancelled!  *Grin*  Not that any of this matters a great deal...<br><br>I have about four and a half blue bubbles of level forty-five left.  Given my current rate of experience gathering, this doesn't seem to bad, since I have only been in level forty-five for about three days.  (Maybe four, I can't remember!)  <i>I have some time off school...  <b>for exams...</b>  So I'm putting in some serious levelling time!</i>  I know, I know.  I'm a bad person!<br><br>My current prey are...  <span style='color: green;'>Bloodgill goblins</span style='color: green;'>.  I hate goblins.  In every fantasy type game they're the bane of my existence.  There's really nothing worse than being killed by a swarm of creatures that really exist beneath your level of notice.  And goblins are the masters of this.<br><br>I have a particularly unpleasant memory of a death in Warsliks woods at the hands of the diabolic green scum.  <i>(For those not familiar with the area, a little South of the zone into The Overthere, is a lake, with Iksar bandits and many many goblins.)</i>  I'm convinced myself and my pet slew at least five goblins, and yet this was not enough.  First my pet and then myself, we fell beneath a forest of claws.<br><br>At the bottom of the lake in the Lake of Ill Omen zone is the sunken temple of Veksar.  It is here that the Bloodgill goblins dwell.  They look much like any other goblin, but are around level forty.  (Which of course makes them a very popular prey for people of a suitably high level...  And a downright menace for anyone else, on the rare occaisions they leave the lake and go wandering...  )  <br><br>As you might imagine, being as popular as they are, many people have their theories as to what is the best manner in which to hunt them.  (Except for quad-kiting druids, who seem to be of the opinion that, <i>'everything in the zone belongs to me and sod the rest of you!'</i>  (I know not <b>all</b> druids are like this, but the class does seem to attract more than it's fair share of wankers!))<br><br>I shall share with you my experience of hunting these greenskinned wretches.  (Goblins, not druids!)  I have learned:<br><LI>Bloodgill goblins hit fairly hard, <b>but</b> they also have very few hitpoints.  (They hit for upwards of eighty points of damage sometimes.  But, at the same time, they seem to have substantially less than two-thousand hitpoints.)  As a practitioner of the dark art of necromancy, I am of course little concerned with how hard an opponnent hits.  No-one is powerful when they're running away screaming like a six-year-old girl.  No-one!<br><LI>There are five spawn points.  Two goblins spawn at each corner of the temple.  (These spawns are too close together to be separated.  You upset one, you get both!)  The fifth spawn point is outside the front door of the temple.  Five goblins spawn in this area.  (Two goblins right in front of the door, two goblins a little further out and a Bloodgill Marauder who spawns just inside the temple.)  <br>If you upset the two on the door, you will get both <b>and</b> the marauder.  The other two can be single pulled very easilly.  (I have read posts to the effect that if you pull <b>any</b> of these goblins, they will all come.  This is not true.  The two furthest out from the door are actually the easiest pulls in the lake!)<br><i>The marauder is much, <b>much</b> tougher than the other goblins.  I have fought him only once, to remove his offensive presence at the request of a solo'ing monk.  (I can happilly take on two Bloodgil goblins at once.  The marauder is harder than this!)  Suffice to say that I do not hunt at the front door.</i><br><LI>Bloodgill goblins are not particularly interested in pursuing their prey.  Every post I have read about hunting Bloodgills requires pulling the goblin to the shore.  I tend to pull using a darkness spell and tried this with the goblins.  If you get only a short way ahead of the goblin, it will return to it's spawn point.  This is both tedious and annoying.  <br>My response to this, has been to hunt the goblins underwater, in their home territory.  Something no-one appears to want to do.  Yet, this has worked very well for me.  <br>In the main, what I am doing that I suspect few have dared to do, is to fear the goblins while not particularly distant from the other spawns.  <i>(I can see why other people may not wish to try this.  But, I am a necromancer, Death is not my enemy!)</i><br>A snared goblin will not get close enough to trigger a goblin at another spawn point.  The goblins from the door will swim toward the pillars onshore.  The goblins at the corners of the temple will swim along the edge of the building toward the center.  I have killed 87 goblins thus far and not once has this occurred.  <i>(Number taken from a log parser.)</i><br>As I have said, two of the door spawns can be single pulled.  On these I cast the following sequence of spells:<br><span style='color: red;'>       Dooming darkness.<br>       <i>Send in pet</i><br>       Invoke fear.<br>       Asystole.<br>       Venom of the Snake.<br><i>Call off pet</i></span style='color: red;'><br>The goblins appear to have a respectable poison resistance, since they can resist VotS a significant amount of the time.  I have tried switching VotS with Chilling Embrace, which I don't recall <b>ever</b> having been resisted.  However, I like the speed at which VotS causes it's harm.<br>By the time I have cast the second DoT, be it VotS, or CE, the goblin will be at a little over half life, ensuring that I get full experience for the kill.<br>If I am pulling on of the double spawns, I Root one goblin and then cast on the second, which attacks.  When this is done, the Rooted goblin receives a similar treatment.  <i>(Root is very rarely resisted, but on the odd occaisions a goblin breaks loose earlier than desired, it can be darked and feared, before applying the DoTs to it's companion.)</i><br><LI>At level forty-five, I have sufficient mana to slay the goblins at on double spawn and one single.  This leaves me with a single bubble of mana, held aside in the event of emergencies.  (It helps that I'm playing in the morning, in the UK.  Today I hunted for perhaps three hours and no-one else was present with an interest in the Bloodgills.)<br>There is no need to leave the lake, other than to meditate.  On several occaisions, I have even killed the goblins at one double spawn and meditated in the water, before moving on to another.  <i>(I am of course using Dead Man Floating.  A minor detail that I should perhaps have mentioned earlier.  But you'd worked that out for yourself, hadn't you?)</i><br><LI>There are at least two Deepwater barracuda spawns in the lake.  These are a little further out from the towers.  The barracuda are around the same level as the goblins, but are a much tougher opponnent.  (And give about the same experience boost.)  The spawns are completely static and the fish will  not move, unless you give them cause to.  Fearing a goblin at the corner spawns will not cause it to approach the fish, so I recommend just ignoring them.<br>There is also a 'Stuffed barracuda' somewhere.  I have targetted it on a few occaisions, when using the auto target.  But, I haven't actually seen it.  (It cons green at level forty-five, so I wasn't too interested!)<br><br><span style='color: purple;'>There is one final lesson...<br><LI>The visibility underwater is appalling.  No doubt everyone is aware that you can put yourself at the same level as the water and thus can see without the reduction of visibility.  I have noticed another means of seeing underwater.  If you are in windowed mode and open your inventory, the murkiness goes away entirely.  (It's conceivable this is a quirk of my PC and video card set-up, but I doubt it.)  Admittedly, you can't do a great deal, once in inventory mode, but it does allow you to have a good look around!</span style='color: purple;'><br><br><span style='color: red;'><b>Bonus information, taken from log parser:</b><br><LI>Bloodgill goblin:<br>       Maximum damage:     78<br><LI>Bloodgill marauder:<br>       Maximum damage:     97</span style='color: red;'><br><i>Looks like I was a little out on the damage they hit for.  What can I tell ya?  *Grin*</i><br><br>Anyhow, This is what I'm up to.  Hopefully, this information might be useful for someone.<br><br>See ya in Norrath.<br><br>AlAaraaf.<br><br><i>(Edited in an attempt to use the pre-formatted text tags.  Absolutely no hope of making it work!  *Grin*)</i><br><br><em id=fs8>Edited, Tue Jan 22 10:26:00 2002</em><br>&nbsp;<br>"Te aurdire no possum. Musa sapienum fixa est in aura."</td></tr>
