ry and otherwise dysfunctional people out there.  (Maybe if they weren't dysfunctional, they wouldn't be playing EverQuest.  *Cackle*)<br>I can see that last remark earning a certain amount of dissent.  So, here is the explanation for the comment:<i><br><LI>I used to use IRC waaaay back when the vast majority of people using the internet were professional people and university students.  (That's the only hint you get, as to how old I am.  But suffice to say I'm older than most of the people on my degree course.)  I used to play text MUDs too.  They were state-of-the-art multiplayer technology!<br><LI>I spoke to and became friends with lots and lots of people.  However, I also spoke to a lot of people who were, well, frankly, not fit to be part of normal society.  People like that are attracted to the internet, 'cos they can hide behind a screen and a keyboard.  (Think about what you read on most forums.  Think about the stuff that lead to the removal of anonymous posting, on the Ranger forum!!!  (I think it was the ranger forum, I could be wrong.)<br><LI>All these human oddities are still out there.  And a good many of them play games such as EverQuest.  This isn't to say that people who play EQ are all insane human chaff.  But, you'll not notice the vast majority of normal people.  The chaff will make themselves known.  (This is perhaps an evolutionary thing.  It's maybe like a diseased plant screaming out, &quot;I'm substandard, weed me out, fer cryin' out loud!!!&quot;)</i><br>Anyhow, that's just my thoughts on the subject.  Just so I don't offend people unnecessarilly.<br>And, going back to the original point, I think they get through the day by trying to drag everyone else down to their level!  <br><span style='color: green;'>&quot;Never argue with an idiot!  They'll drag you down to their own level and then beat you with experience.&quot;</span style='color: green;'><br><br><i>I guess they vent it on the boards, huh? Probably very cathartic to post &q