	   <tr><td colspan=2>Hey.<br><br>It's been a wee while and I guess I owe you a new post.&nbsp;&nbsp;(I should be working, but I really can't be bothered.  I should maybe have done everything before Christmas, 'cos I've just sorta ground to a halt.  *Groan*  If I don't start soon, I'm gonna end up with a last minute panic on my hands.  Anyone fancy creating a website for me?)<br><br>Today, in a round-about way, let us consider quests.  There are two in particular I have in mind...<br><br><b>The Rallic pack:</b><br>There is a quest in Katta Castellum, which results in a rather nice, ten slot, eighty five percent weight reduction pack.  <i>(Isn't that a rather wonderful reward?)</i>  <br>The short version of what you have to do, is this:<br><LI>Speak to Rallik.  (Close to Tenebrous zone.)<br><LI>Kill a Grimling Runner, get a bag from it and give it to Rallik.<br><LI>Get a pattern fro Rallik.<br><LI>Tailor the bag from the pattern, a perfect owlbear pelt and a shadeling silk cord to get the bag.<br>The Grimling Runner is apparently pretty easy to solo at around level forty.  And the bag is trivial to tailor at seventeen skill in tailoring.  Sounds remarkably easy for such a desirable item, doesn't it?<br><i>{The quest isn't listed on Allakhazam's <b>Yet</b>.  I got my information from EQTraders.  Follow <a href=HTTP://pub13.ezboard.com/feqtraderscornerfrm65.showMessage?topicID=27.topic target=_new>this link</a> to read more.}</i><br>Now, while I'm not going to suggest for a single second, that this isn't a highly desirable item, I also came across these two comments on the same site:<br><LI><i>&quot;People!! PLEASE do NOT underprice these... I have two orders for these already. One guy is paying 2k. The other is paying 1.5k. Thank you&quot;</i><br><LI><i>&quot;don't be foolish if you sell these for under 4k unless to guildies your insane&quot;</i><br>...............<b>GREED</b><br>Frankly, this seems a lot like trying to sell a Stein of Moggok for a thousand platinum pieces.  While the item is desirable, the effort required to obtain one, is pretty limited.  It's not like asking someone to make you an item that requires they have a high tradeskill.  (Seventeen doesn't seem that high to me.  Am I just jaded???)<br><i>It does of course require that you can walk freely in Katta Castellum, but for many people this requires no work.</i><br>I often find myself thinking that I have a low opinion of the species in general.  But, people who make statements like these, just reinforce the low opinion.  It disgusts me.  <br><b>Pay the blood sucking leeches in counterfeit coins...  Preferably ones that explode!</b><br>&quot;I have here a purse of monies...  Which I am not going to give to you!&quot;<br><br><b>Feeding the Coldain:</b><br>This quest, <b>is</b>, of course, very well known.  I am currently at the stage where I am collecting snow griffon eggs.  Sadly, it is not feasible to sneak up to a snow griffon nest and swipe the eggs, while mommy bird is away getting some lunch.  (Does a griffon count as a bird?  Hey, why not?  It has wings, it flies and it lays eggs.  That makes it a bird in my book!)<br>Despite the complaints of many people, I haven't had horrific difficulties finding griffons.  Which is not to say that I'm finding them by the bushel.  (Largey because griffons wouldn't fit in a bushel!)  But, while lurking about in the region of the Sleeper's tomb, I'm found and slain about half a dozen so far.  <br>I'm finding it rather satisfying murdering them, largely, since the first one slashed me up rather efficiently, when I forgot to re-fear it.  (A mistake I have been careful not to repeat.)<br>As a small aside, anyone who hasn't seen the tomb of the Sleeper, you should really go and have a look.  It's one of these areas of Norrath, where Verant have excelled themselves.  Obviously, I haven't seen inside, but just go look at the carving of the sleeping dragon.  Satisfaction guaranteed, or your money back!  <br><i>&quot;Do you have that in writing, sir?  No, well, then I'm afraid I can't help you!&quot;</i><br>I have, thus far, for all my griffon slaying escapades, one egg!  I'm told the eggs are an uncommon drops, so I guess if the law of averages are with me, I need to kill maybe another fifteen to twenty griffons.  Which I guess is not too painful.<br>Well, not too painful, assuming that I don't fail when I try to make the griffon egg souffle.  (Would Thoridain notice if I used snake eggs?  I bet he wouldn't!  Hey, he's a dwarf, I could probably give him a piece of coal on a plate and tell him it got a bit burnt.  It's not like they sharpest sticks in the stack!)<br>This just strikes me as a pretty diabolical requirement for a quest.  Four uncommon drops, off uncommon creatures.  It's particularly annoying, because all the wanderers in the zone keep attacking me.  I was about to attack a griffon at one point today when a dervish attacked me.  No problem at all.  All I had to do was quickly slay the dervish and get the griffon, before it flew off.  Nope!  Before the first dervish died, another joined in.  Then a tundra kodiak.  And then a snow cougar.  All of them were probably green and really not much of an issue.  But by the time I'd rid myself of them, I was at fifty percent mana and the griffon was nowhere to be seen!  <br>...../em grinds his teeth.<br>I should just try giving Thoridain something else.  I'm sure the short fool wouldn't notice!<br>No big deal with this quest, it's just what I'm doing.  Unlike the last one, which has left me very unimpressed.  <br><br>As an aside, today has been a day of close escapes.  I've spet the last coupla days working on tradeskills.  I got my tailoring up to eighty-one and decided it was time to start thinking about tailoring crystalline silk.  <br>So, I took myself along to the Crystal caverns.  Happily, the spider caves were not occupied, so I set about slaughtering the eight-legged denizens therein.  This worked out very well and I am loaded up with a small pile of crystal silks.  <br>For some reason the drachnid retainer decided to come wandering up the hall on two occasons.  But i was rather pleased to discover I won both times.  (And gained a coupla items I'll dump on my pitifully low level alts, since I hate sitting about auctioning things.)<br>Less pleasing, was the occasion a crystal grinder showed up in the middle of a fight.  One spider is no problem.  Two and my pet gets messed up.  Three can be rather tricky.  Three and a crystal grinder is just a horrible mess.  Ultimately, I ended up FD'd on the floor with no pet.  This wouldn't be so bad, if I wasn't FD'd under a spider's spawn point.<br>It's surprisingly difficult to convince people to come and beat up two spiders, so you don't die!  In the end, I had to wait until I had enough HPs to get up, run a bit further down the hall and feign death again!<br>After this, I decided I had enough silks!<br>The reason I started hunting griffons today, was that I got lost looking for the Ry'Gorr camp!  (It was snowing!  Just because I have one hundred and seventy-five skill in sense heading, doesn't mean I know where I am...  It just means I know where I'm goin'!)<br>I found a griffon and decided maybe I should work on the third shawl quest.  I mean, I've only been ready to do it for three months, or so.  So, I cast a pet and then, snared and feared the griffon.  All fine and dandy.  As I said above, it broke fear and beat the bejeesus outta me.  But I can't blame it for trying.  At the end of it, I had one bubble of mana and about half of my HP left.  I cast Gather Shadows, dismissing my pet and sat down outta the way.<br>Big mistake.<br>While I sit, minding my own business, my invisibility drops and a manticore decides that an Iksar is exactly the source of protein it needs.  Happily, I managed to feign death in time to save myself once again!  Slightly les happily, I was poisoned and died anyway!  <br>As a curious aside, I was slain by 'Pain and suffering.'  As an even more curious aside, Pain and suffering tried to strike me three times and missed!  How does that work?<br>My third close call, was also while wandering around the Eastern Wastes.  I came across a dwarf standing around on his own.  I spoke unto him and he said he had been ambushed by giants.  He then asked that I vanquish these giants and give him a potion, to be obtained by the leader of the giants.  At this point, about half a dozen giants swarmed over me, beating me to a pulp.  (Oh joy, of joys.  Still, it's only fair.  Talk to strange dwarven men and you should expect these things to happen!)<br>Once again, I ended up lying prone, while waiting for whomever had beaten me up to go away!  On the upside, the giants must've beated the pulp outta the dwarf too, since he vanished.  That makes me feel a little better.  (I might go talk to him again a few times and just immediately feign death, to watch 'em beat the crap outta him.  It seems only just!)<br><br>So, a final thought...<br><br>I want the bazaar to work!  I hate auctioning.  I just loathe the idea of sitting around in East Commonlands, shouting my wares like a common peasant.  And frankly, I don't much fancy watching lines and lines of auctions scroll by, either seeing nothing I want, seeing something I want that's waaaaay outta my pricerange, or seeing something I want, sending a tell and finding it's sold already.<br>The idea of setting up as a merchant at the bazaar seems ideal to me.  (I have a cable modem, I can leave the PC on all night, quite happily!)  Obviously, it's not ideal for everyone.  Not everyone can leave their PC running overnight.  And not everyone has SoL.  But I wish more people would use the bazaar.  But, every time I go there, it's empty.  *Sigh*<br><br>Anyhow, that's enough for tonight, I think.  Take care and I'll see ya wanderin' around Norrath.<br><br>AlAaraaf<br>&nbsp;<br>"Te aurdire no possum. Musa sapienum fixa est in aura."</td></tr>
